-- China Vanke, Kia Motors, Tradewinds, Wilmar: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- Berni Moestafa
-- 2010-06-21T21:29:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/china-vanke-kia-motors-tradewinds-wilmar-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in  Asian trading , excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  
 Developers: Chinese property prices in larger cities are
poised to steadily decline as government measures start to take
effect, the National Development and Reform Commission said in a
report relating to 36 large and medium-sized cities. It didn’t
name the cities.  
 China Vanke Co.  (000002 CH), the nation’s biggest listed
property developer, added 3.8 percent to 7.34 yuan.  Poly Real
Estate Group Co.  (600048 CH), the second-largest, rose 5.2
percent to 11.80 yuan.  
 China Strategic Holdings Ltd.  (235 HK): The company and
Primus Financial Holdings Ltd. extended an agreement with
American International Group Inc. to purchase the U.S. company’s
Taiwanese insurance unit. The agreement to acquire Nan Shan Life
Insurance Co. was extended until Oct. 12, according to an e-
mailed statement from Primus. China Strategic gained 3.6 percent
to 57 Hong Kong cents.  
 EEI Corp.  (EEI PM): The Philippine construction company was
lowered to “hold” from “buy” with a 12-month share price
estimate of 4.20 pesos a share by ATR KimEng Securities Inc.
analyst  Katherine Tan . The stock climbed 3.9 percent to 4.05
pesos.  
 Kia Motors Corp.  (000270 KS): South Korea’s second-biggest
carmaker plans to cut debt by repaying 300 million euros ($374
million) of bonds without selling new securities to replace them,
according to three people with knowledge of the matter. Kia will
use cash to repay its floating-rate notes due on June 24, the
people said, declining to be identified as no announcement has
been made. Kia Motors fell 0.3 percent to 31,800 won.  
 Korea Exchange Bank  (004940 KS): MBK Partners Ltd. was the
sole bidder for Lone Star Funds’ controlling stake in Korea
Exchange Bank, Yonhap News reported, citing a financial industry
official it didn’t identify. Korea Exchange Bank advanced 0.4
percent to 13,450 won.  
 Tradewinds Corp.  (TWC MK): The Malaysian property,
plantation and construction group said it named Arief Nasran
Abdul Wahab as group chief operating officer. He will assume the
functions of Group Chief Executive Officer Shaharul  Farez bin Hassan , who is on 14 months sabbatical leave, the company said
in a statement. Tradewinds added 4.4 percent to 59 sen.  
 Wilmar International Ltd.  (WIL SP): The world’s largest
palm-oil trader plans to invest $2 billion in Indonesia, the
Information Ministry said on its website, citing  Gita Wirjawan ,
head of the nation’s investment board. Wilmar  may invest  in
various industries, including agriculture in Merauke, a town on
Papua island, Wirjawan was cited as saying. Singapore-based
Wilmar rose 3.3 percent to S$6.02.  
